<div id="review_428376437" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/428376437" />
    <a title="Katie" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/706193-katie"><img alt="Katie" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1198856875p2/706193.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/428376437?book_show_action=true">Oct 05, 2012</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Katie" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Katie" href="/user/show/706193-katie">Katie</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer428376437" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14325822767918322728">Excellent book, about a happy (and sometimes miserable, and everything in between) marriage. It&apos;s got to be hugely autobiographical, since the author, like the protagonist, lost his wife to illness recently, and also dropped out of high school when he got his first book published. I couldn&apos;t help wondering where the author ended and the character began. The book is a beautifully-structured description of a fascinating relationship between two people, from when they first met to when the wife suc</span>
  <span id="freeText14325822767918322728" style="display:none">Excellent book, about a happy (and sometimes miserable, and everything in between) marriage. It's got to be hugely autobiographical, since the author, like the protagonist, lost his wife to illness recently, and also dropped out of high school when he got his first book published. I couldn't help wondering where the author ended and the character began. The book is a beautifully-structured description of a fascinating relationship between two people, from when they first met to when the wife succumbs to terminal illness. It sounds like it's going to be a bummer but it's not, and from the title it sounds like it's going to be all about their happiness, but it's not.<br /><br />The best part of this book was the sharp, witty writing. It's one of "those" books, where you keep going back and re-reading perfect phrases, thinking "how did he come UP with that?" I'm definitely looking up this author's other books based on this one.<br /><br />Also excellent was the structure and the characters. The story kept flipping back and forth between when they first met and modern-day (where the wife is dying). The author also kept dropping little breadcrumbs, hinting at various future events that have yet to be explained--and he made good on all of them. He'd just casually mention something rather groundbreaking in a chapter and you'd think, "wait, WHAT??" and then not mention it again until a few chapters later when it gets fully explored. That kept me on my toes (in a good way).<br /><br />The in-depth exploration of their close relationship meant you got to learn all about these two characters, warts and all. The wife is certainly not depicted as a saint--she definitely has her bad characteristics--but she was so expertly drawn that you almost fall in love with her too by the end of the book.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14325822767918322728" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


