    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_156482014" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/156482014" />
    <a title="nicole" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/35523-nicole"><img alt="nicole" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1222397490p2/35523.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/156482014?book_show_action=true">Mar 24, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="nicole" class="user" itemprop="url" name="nicole" href="/user/show/35523-nicole">nicole</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/35523-nicole?shelf=2011">2011</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer156482014" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14962678404359761362">You know right off the bat this book is going to be sad. It doesn&apos;t mince words. At the end of the book, Margaret is going to die. And the author&apos;s wife really died of cancer, so this is only one foot in fiction. Many reviews use the word expansive to politely describe this, but I felt it to be staggering. The book physically became harder to hold as certain scenes were retold. The depth of details as she fell apart. The constant return to the present day after being gloriously ingrained in the </span>
  <span id="freeText14962678404359761362" style="display:none">You know right off the bat this book is going to be sad. It doesn't mince words. At the end of the book, Margaret is going to die. And the author's wife really died of cancer, so this is only one foot in fiction. Many reviews use the word expansive to politely describe this, but I felt it to be staggering. The book physically became harder to hold as certain scenes were retold. The depth of details as she fell apart. The constant return to the present day after being gloriously ingrained in the past. <br /><br />I've been thinking a lot about marriage so much, lately. I have always been fascinated by strong marriages, having not been the product of one. As a child of divorce, I feel a little like a field reporter when I come across people who are still married. I am still startled when I see someone else's parents kiss. But now that I am in a relationship that I'd like to see continue to move forward, I'm even more perplexed by what it takes to make something last, even in the worst of times. What is their secret, I wonder, taking out my tape recording device and field notebook.<br /><br />But I didn't find out much I didn't know before. What I did a lot of was sob. And sob. And sob some more. Well-written and not overly literary, but not the sort of thing you'd recommend lightly. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14962678404359761362" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


